# Architecture Health LLM Guide

## Purpose

Use this command to get a compact architecture preflight: boundary status, shape status, unmapped files, hotspots, and dependency-pressure clusters.

## When To Run

- Before starting a non-trivial implementation.
- After touching imports, module seams, or feature structure.
- Before finalizing work when you need one architecture-oriented summary.

## How To Read The Result

- Boundary and shape findings are blockers when marked as errors.
- Unknown files are classification signals, not automatic failures.
- Hotspots point to module-size or dependency-pressure areas worth treating carefully.
- Pressure clusters show likely blast radius and shared-code gravity.

## Examples

- If boundaries or shape report errors, fix those before summarizing the work.
- If unknown files appear, inspect local rules before moving or editing them.
- If a high-pressure cluster is involved, prefer smaller commits and rerun checks often.
- If health passes but shows attention findings, mention the residual risk briefly.

## Agent Tips

- Use this as an overview, not a replacement for focused boundary or shape checks.
- Follow up with `architecture boundaries` when changing dependency direction.
- Follow up with `architecture shape` after editing imports or public code shape.
- Do not treat hotspot ranking as ownership policy; policy comes from the contract.
